WORLD ROUND-UP
---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CHINA: Army of graduates struggles for jobs

In 1998 when Jiang Zemin, then president of China, announced plans to
bolster higher education, universities and colleges produced 830,000
graduates a year. Last May, that number was more than six million and
rising, writes Andrew Jacobs for the New York Times.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217221943951

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

SOUTH KOREA: Slew of foreign universities to open=20

A slew of universities based in Europe and the United States are set to
open their South Korean campuses at the Incheon Free Economic Zone (FEZ),
40 kilometres west of Seoul, starting next year, reports the Korea Herald.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217221853281

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

CHINA: UK visa rules may force Chinese student exodus

Tens of thousands of Chinese students in the United Kingdom could be forced
out of the country if a basket of strict visa policies takes effect next
year, write Chen Jia and Aid Yang for China Daily.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217221751302

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

IRELAND: Academy relieved at =91modest=92 cuts

Universities have expressed relief following the relatively modest cuts to
higher education funding announced in the Republic of Ireland=92s emergency
budget last week, writes Hannah Fearn for Times Higher Education.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217221658141

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UAE: Universities face 2011 spending freeze=20

The federal government will run a Dh3 billion (US$800 million) budget
deficit next year and will freeze spending by state universities, writes
Kareem Shaheen for The National.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217221518687

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Tuition fee hike open to human rights challenge

Lawyers say allowing universities to raise fees to =A39,000 (US$14,071) cou=
ld
be open to legal challenge, as it will discriminate against students from
poorer backgrounds, writes Jeevan Vasagar for The Guardian.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217221241845

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: =91Dearth of blacks at Oxford and Cambridge=92

David Lammy, a former higher education minister and Labour Member of
Parliament, has used figures obtained under Britain=92s Freedom of
Information Law to reveal a dearth of black and other minority students at
either of the country=92s two oldest universities, reports DD Guttenplan for
The New York Times.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217221137976

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Disquiet over motives behind pension overhaul

Controversial plans to cut benefits in higher education=92s =A330 billion
(US$46.9 billion) pension fund have prompted staff rebellions at a growing
number of universities, as evidence has emerged that employers want to
slash their contributions to the scheme, writes John Morgan for Times
Higher Education.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217221027899

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

MALAYSIA: Five-year moratorium on medical courses

The Malaysian government will impose a five-year moratorium on medical
programmes as an immediate measure to prevent the glut in housemen from
becoming worse, write Richard Lim and Loh Foon Fong for The Star.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217220907808

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

MALAYSIA: Council formed to boost R&D=20

A National Science and Research Council (NSRC) will be set up in Malaysia
to prepare for the creation of a national research system based on science
and technology in a more conducive environment, reports the official agency
Bernama.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D2010121722065890

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

SRI LANKA: Government to attract foreign students=20

Along with the major overhaul in Sri Lanka=92s higher education sector, with
the entry of private universities by April next year, government plans to
attract about 10,000 foreign students into local universities, and another
50,000 into Sri Lanka in the longer term through the proposed private
universities, writes Chandani Kirinde for The Sunday Times.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217220539329

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

GHANA: Polytechnic lecturers move to universities

The Polytechnic Teachers Association of Ghana, Potag, says its members have
begun moving to universities to teach due to difficulties in negotiating
for better conditions of service. It has called on the government to soften
its stance regarding negotiating with polytechnic teachers, reports Peace
FM.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D2010121722044779

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UGANDA: Museveni pledges support for scientists

Uganda=92s President Yoweri Museveni last week pledged continued support to
scientists to boost their efforts towards developing the country, writes
Patience Ahimbisibwe for The Daily Monitor.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217220355827

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

N IGERIA: =91Universities must breed credible leaders=92

The Speaker of N igeria=92s House of Representatives, Dimeji Bankole, has
passed on the responsibility of curtailing public office holders from
misappropriating funds to universities, which he said must reclaim their
roles as the breeders of credible leaders, writes Onche Odeh for The Daily
Independent.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217220259393

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

US: For-profits rake in millions from GI Bill

For-profit universities collected about US$640 million from the Post-9/11
GI Bill in its first year, according to a new US Senate committee document,
reports TPM LiveWire. The boost to for-profits came at a time when the
sector was subject to criticism for poor results and for leaving many
students with unmanageable debts.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217215947419

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

UK: Publishing giant Pearson poised to offer degrees

One of the world=92s largest publishers, Pearson, looks set to be given
degree-awarding powers, as the government seeks to open up the university
sector to more private providers, reports the BBC.
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217215753961

---------------------------------------------------------------------------

VIET NAM: Universities play role in green thinking

Universities have actively contributed to the way people think about
climate change, helping to promote green technologies and environmentally
friendly lifestyles, reports Viet Nam News.=20
More on the University World News site:
http://www.universityworldnews.com/article.php?story=3D20101217215756965


